    {
      "key": "09de7116-a992-49a7-a6d9-49eb09c8dfb6",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "09de7116-a992-49a7-a6d9-49eb09c8dfb6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "aef1899c-d72e-48b5-a32e-f47144a390ba"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bd3d9a5c-e5b2-4384-befc-2bb413250afb",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their The Fabric of the Internet and AI Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Give students a quick minute to jot down their thoughts on the Question of the Day. Encourage students to include at least one specific example from any of today’s activities.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in groups of three or four.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to briefly share in one or two sentences how websites find their way to your browser using DNS and HTTP. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen to small-group conversations and if time permits, call on two or three groups to share their key insights with the class.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to build on each other’s ideas instead of just repeating the same answer. "
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day effectively assesses the lesson objectives if students provide responses that explain:\n- how DNS resolves domain names into IP addresses.\n- the function of HTTP in requesting web pages."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bd3d9a5c-e5b2-4384-befc-2bb413250afb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eca9aea6-1fce-4689-9d93-5b32a282ee4f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0d3d33aa-83ab-4ee5-b80b-cbc1a2d2c3ee",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0d3d33aa-83ab-4ee5-b80b-cbc1a2d2c3ee",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eca9aea6-1fce-4689-9d93-5b32a282ee4f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "282ce24a-85d5-4b20-8cfc-1f6cacaff8e1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How do websites use DNS and HTTP to load in your browser?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Listen for answers that synthesize the process: DNS translates domain names into IP addresses, and HTTP uses GET requests to retrieve content from servers, working together to bring websites to life."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "282ce24a-85d5-4b20-8cfc-1f6cacaff8e1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "eca9aea6-1fce-4689-9d93-5b32a282ee4f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4ba42cf3-70a2-42ee-baa8-275460d64592",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain the Four Corners upcoming activity to students. Make sure to point out which corner will be **Yes**, **No**, **Maybe**, and **Undecided**.\n\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If your classroom can’t accommodate movement or you have students uncomfortable sharing in large groups, consider using “Line Debate” (students hold up fingers to show agreement level) or silent discussion protocols like “Chalk Talk” or digital polls."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4ba42cf3-70a2-42ee-baa8-275460d64592",
        "lesson_activity.key": "64f53b43-8150-41de-a12c-556ca08a2486"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f9f94666-6b68-42f2-a087-894284feb938",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f9f94666-6b68-42f2-a087-894284feb938",
        "lesson_activity.key": "64f53b43-8150-41de-a12c-556ca08a2486"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d8470e7e-4643-4a7d-9111-c8b006e32802",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the first scenario to students and direct them to move to the corner that best aligns whether they agree, disagree, think maybe or are unsure. Instruct students to discuss their reasoning with others who share their stance and then call on a student from each corner to share why their group chose their position.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage critical thinking about fairness, competition, and access on the Internet as well as cost barriers, freedom of information, or business interests."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d8470e7e-4643-4a7d-9111-c8b006e32802",
        "lesson_activity.key": "64f53b43-8150-41de-a12c-556ca08a2486"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ac83e3fd-7a01-4f26-b30d-738155ce46da",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ac83e3fd-7a01-4f26-b30d-738155ce46da",
        "lesson_activity.key": "64f53b43-8150-41de-a12c-556ca08a2486"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cf554487-243e-4e64-9ef3-f88356fd8cd2",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the second scenario to students and direct them to move to the corner that best aligns whether they agree, disagree, think maybe or are unsure. Instruct students to discuss their reasoning with others who share their stance and then call on a student from each corner who was not a spokesperson for scenario #1 to share why their group chose their position.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Read the third scenario to students and direct them to move to the corner that best aligns whether they agree, disagree, think maybe or are unsure. Instruct students to discuss their reasoning with others who share their stance and then call on a student from each corner who was not a spokesperson for the previous two scenarios to share why their group chose their position.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce Net Neutrality to students and that all of the scenarios relate to net neutrality. Explain to students that this means that without net neutrality, Internet Service Providers (ISPs) can prioritize, slow down or even block websites and companies can pay for faster access creating advantages for some and barriers for others. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Net neutrality impacts who has access to fast, reliable Internet and who is left behind. If an ISP charges extra for faster speeds, who might struggle to afford it? How could this deepen the digital divide? Encourage students to think about these questions throughout the lesson. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cf554487-243e-4e64-9ef3-f88356fd8cd2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "64f53b43-8150-41de-a12c-556ca08a2486"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d57e9538-fc03-4a2d-934e-1d8331122603",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d57e9538-fc03-4a2d-934e-1d8331122603",
        "lesson_activity.key": "64f53b43-8150-41de-a12c-556ca08a2486"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f5b669cb-3a75-4dcd-9a8c-48baa5319450",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to make direct connections between each scenario and net neutrality. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f5b669cb-3a75-4dcd-9a8c-48baa5319450",
        "lesson_activity.key": "64f53b43-8150-41de-a12c-556ca08a2486"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4683aaf9-b7c4-494f-bf01-55d1a08b44f2",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Put students in groups of two. Make sure students have their Unit Guides out and turned to Lesson 7 to record their observations in the next activity.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Level 1 to complete Levels 1 through 5 to investigate the data from the Pew Research Center about Internet Access and discuss the questions with their partner.\n- **Level 1:** Students explore internet use over time.\n- **Level 2:** Students explore home broadband use by income.\n- **Level 3:** Students explore internet use by community type.\n- **Level 4:** Students explore internet use by age.\n- **Level 5:** Students explore smartphone dependency by education.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Digital Divide Data Analysis",
        "progression_name": "Pew Research Center: Internet Access"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4683aaf9-b7c4-494f-bf01-55d1a08b44f2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "227d2afa-795c-4fa1-8f45-16c5fecbc176"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f1e44cc5-3339-4330-a5f5-000ad3a58054",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to record their observations in their Unit Guides as they discuss the questions on each level."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f1e44cc5-3339-4330-a5f5-000ad3a58054",
        "lesson_activity.key": "227d2afa-795c-4fa1-8f45-16c5fecbc176"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bb41a2e7-e996-438d-9b6a-851c7589fac6",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that we understand net neutrality, let’s explore the bigger picture: Who actually has access to the Internet? Together, we will look at the data from Pew Research and think about who benefits most and who gets left behind. I will put the graphs up on the board. You will also have a version of these graphs on your own computer so you can see them more clearly. ",
        "remarks": true,
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "In each level, students will have the opportunity to look at the interactive version of each graph by clicking on the link within each level. If time allows, encourage students to open the link in a new tab and use the “find” tool on their browser to quickly find the graph on the report page. Hovering over each data point will give them more information about the graph. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bb41a2e7-e996-438d-9b6a-851c7589fac6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "227d2afa-795c-4fa1-8f45-16c5fecbc176"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "26786c2c-5a19-4d5b-8bfa-838e4c6bcd69",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "26786c2c-5a19-4d5b-8bfa-838e4c6bcd69",
        "lesson_activity.key": "227d2afa-795c-4fa1-8f45-16c5fecbc176"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7972b8ca-8eab-4237-abed-c629d0caaf15",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to display possible answers to the annotated graph and discuss what students notice and are surprised by.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What do you notice about Internet access across different groups (e.g., income, geography, age)?*\n- *How might these disparities impact education, employment, or civic participation?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that Internet access is not distributed equally and that disparities exist based on income, geography, education, and age. Encourage students to connect these inequalities to opportunities in education, employment, and civic engagement, considering how limited access can reinforce existing societal divides. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out their The Fabric of the Internet and AI Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the digital divide to students."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7972b8ca-8eab-4237-abed-c629d0caaf15",
        "lesson_activity.key": "227d2afa-795c-4fa1-8f45-16c5fecbc176"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2118d768-f855-4e52-af7c-6e0ed94d2b0b",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Internet Access IRL activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 6 to choose one of the AI Chatbot personas that has been affected by the digital divide.",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Case Studies with AI Chatbot",
        "progression_name": "Choose a Persona"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2118d768-f855-4e52-af7c-6e0ed94d2b0b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "227d2afa-795c-4fa1-8f45-16c5fecbc176"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a94fb0d9-fd64-47e8-b543-1c5d16f094cc",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen for student discussions about access barriers (e.g., cost, availability, slow speeds). Prompt students to think whether the persona's experience compares to their own.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n- *What did you learn about your persona?*\n- *How does this connect to the disparities we saw in the Pew Research data?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The goal of this discussion is to help students connect real-world technology access disparities to the personas they explored and the data from Pew Research. Students should recognize how limited access to the Internet affects different aspects of life, including education, jobs, healthcare, and civic participation. Finally, encourage them to think critically about possible solutions, including the role of policies like net neutrality in shaping digital equity."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a94fb0d9-fd64-47e8-b543-1c5d16f094cc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "227d2afa-795c-4fa1-8f45-16c5fecbc176"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "81709fb6-3ac4-4a03-9b87-a103b3c01aaf",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "81709fb6-3ac4-4a03-9b87-a103b3c01aaf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "227d2afa-795c-4fa1-8f45-16c5fecbc176"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4eef9acf-6a98-4125-87de-39b742997b84",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to write a short response to the Question of the Day and then have student pair up to share responses. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Question of the Day effectively assesses the lesson objectives if students provide responses that explain:\n- the impact of the digital divide on different populations and potential solutions to address it.\n- Net neutrality and digital divide issues shape opportunities in education, jobs, and civic life."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4eef9acf-6a98-4125-87de-39b742997b84",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5a6f7844-b747-4a89-bd42-fa04dc65cbf0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ab98de7d-e08d-488c-ae8c-ba81b364877e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:**  Show the video “Qualcomm Engineers are Improving Safety and Livelihoods for Fishermen in India”. \n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What challenges did the fishermen face without Internet access, and how do similar barriers affect other communities? How did technology help them, and how could AI improve Internet access for others?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goals:**Students should discuss the barriers to Internet access and recognize that limited connectivity impacts more than just convenience—it affects safety, economic stability, and access to resources. Guide students to identify the specific challenges faced by the fishermen in the video and consider how similar barriers exist in other communities. Encourage students to think about how technology, including AI, can play a role in solving these access issues, setting up connections to their advocacy project.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Warm Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ab98de7d-e08d-488c-ae8c-ba81b364877e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0aaf3ce-f89d-4a2f-b090-c3b11c4259e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "765c98eb-ae0c-42f2-bd26-71d06d8caef3",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students into groups of 2-3.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:**  Give each group a copy of the Internet Access Advocacy Campaign Project Planning Guide. This will guide them through all three days of the project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Explain to students that for the next three days, they will work as Internet Access Advocates. This means they will explore real-world challenges related to equitable Internet access, the digital divide, and net neutrality. They will analyze case studies, assess the societal and ethical impacts of these issues, and develop persuasive advocacy campaigns with actionable and AI-driven solutions. Along the way, they will refine their messages through peer review and collaborative discussions.\n\n",
        "duration": "35",
        "name": "Activity",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Depending on your class schedule and student pacing, this project may take 3 to 5 class periods to complete. If you're aiming to complete it in 3 days, consider these in-class adjustments:\n- Use timers to keep groups on track during Gallery Walk and Design Sprint\n- Offer 2–3 focused campaign format options to streamline production\n- Keep the pitch draft informal (bullet points, not full scripts) during peer feedback\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "765c98eb-ae0c-42f2-bd26-71d06d8caef3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0aaf3ce-f89d-4a2f-b090-c3b11c4259e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a2b4380f-361e-4589-a5ef-9bfc34c1055d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a2b4380f-361e-4589-a5ef-9bfc34c1055d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0aaf3ce-f89d-4a2f-b090-c3b11c4259e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b6e990d5-2b64-4408-b1db-b30362bf74c8",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the first part of the project requirements and answer any questions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the rest of the project requirements and answer any questions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to read the project rubric and hold on to any questions they may have.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.*What do you notice about the project rubric?\n- *What does success look like for this project?*\n- *What do you notice about the project rubric?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students share what they notice about the project requirements and rubric and identify the tasks they will need to complete for this project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What barriers do you anticipate to achieving success on this project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students identify barriers they anticipate and share any questions they have about the project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the steps students will take on Day 1.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the steps students will take on Day 2.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the steps students will take on Day 3.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Gallery Walk Info Tracker.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Place students into groups of three or four. These groups should be different than who they are working with on the project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Go over the activity instructions with students. Explain that their group will visit each station, read the scenario, and record key information on their project planning guide. Emphasize the importance of focusing on examples, evidence, and key issues for their advocacy campaign.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Assign each corner a persona (Diego, Lisa, Mr. Johnson, Aisha) and direct groups to visit stations, read scenarios, and record key issues, evidence, and examples on their project guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:**  As students explore the personas, ask: ‘How does this individual’s experience reflect a larger issue with Internet access? What groups face similar barriers?’ If students are only summarizing without analyzing, prompt them to think about solutions: ‘What policies or technologies could improve this person’s access to the Internet?",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Adjust structure as needed—assign starting stations, use a timer for rotations, or provide a digital version with links to each station."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b6e990d5-2b64-4408-b1db-b30362bf74c8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0aaf3ce-f89d-4a2f-b090-c3b11c4259e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "49f4d2c2-fd12-4a1b-a269-ebf3b6c9fdf2",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "49f4d2c2-fd12-4a1b-a269-ebf3b6c9fdf2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0aaf3ce-f89d-4a2f-b090-c3b11c4259e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "befbb177-e946-463a-bd4b-b7a697c36add",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Students should move into their project groups and prepare to discuss insights from the gallery walk. Assign or review team roles (Manager, Summarizer, Recorder, Time Keeper). They will use their notes to identify key issues, examples, and target groups for their advocacy campaign.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to debrief their Gallery Walks with their group. Ensure group Recorders are recording responses in the group’s Project Planning Guide.  \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As groups are discussing, use probing questions to support groups who may be stuck (e.g., “How does this evidence connect to your focus?”). Check shared notes and provide feedback to strengthen their ideas. Keep groups on track by reminding Time Keepers of the schedule.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slides to discuss different types of advocacy campaigns with students. Briefly explain each format (e.g., social media video, PSA, infographic) and ask students to consider which format would best suit their message and audience. Encourage them to think about clarity, reach, and impact when selecting a campaign type.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to turn to the Design Sprint page in their Advocacy Project Planning Guide. Instruct them to discuss each prompt as a group and record a common answer. Remind them to use team roles (Manager, Summarizer, Recorder, Time Keeper) to stay organized and ensure everyone contributes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Encourage students to move beyond identifying problems and focus on action. Ask: ‘What specific change do you want to see? How will your campaign convince others to care about this issue?’ If students struggle with persuasion, suggest they include a real-world example or statistic to strengthen their argument.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": " If students need more support, consider distributing a Persona Summary Sheet to each group. This quick-reference overview can help students connect real-world challenges to their campaign solutions.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "befbb177-e946-463a-bd4b-b7a697c36add",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0aaf3ce-f89d-4a2f-b090-c3b11c4259e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0d294bdf-d629-4c5c-8f84-3816f619d20e",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0d294bdf-d629-4c5c-8f84-3816f619d20e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0aaf3ce-f89d-4a2f-b090-c3b11c4259e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dbdee0fc-c13c-4504-80fb-0db25f646e8c",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What stood out to you the most today? Why does this issue matter? What can we do about it?*\n- Use the Three W's protocol to facilitate this discussion. First, students discuss answers in pairs or small groups. Then , select three or four students to share a takeaway.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should reflect on key takeaways from the lesson and connect the digital divide to real-world impacts. Guide them to recognize who is affected, why it matters, and how advocacy can drive change. This discussion will set the stage for their advocacy campaigns by helping them consider how to make their message compelling and actionable.",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Wrap Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dbdee0fc-c13c-4504-80fb-0db25f646e8c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c0aaf3ce-f89d-4a2f-b090-c3b11c4259e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6e337c38-5e52-40f0-8ab4-0d1417a495bf",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:**  Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.****\n- *What key issue did your group decide to focus on?*\n- *What evidence or examples did you identify to support your campaign?*\n- *What is one challenge or question your group still needs to address?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:**  Students should articulate their campaign’s key message and analyze whether their current plan effectively supports it. Encourage them to identify missing evidence or areas where their message could be stronger, ensuring their campaign is clear, compelling, and action-oriented.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:**  Ensure students are making direct connections between their focus and evidence. Ask guiding questions:*“How does your campaign address a real-world problem?”*and*“What additional information would strengthen your argument?”*",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Warm Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6e337c38-5e52-40f0-8ab4-0d1417a495bf",
        "lesson_activity.key": "95b57443-3696-49c6-bfc3-001aa3ab9497"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1c4a6fbf-7570-4231-8100-23544cff5baa",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "duration": "35",
        "name": "Activity",
        "progression_name": "Student Survey"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1c4a6fbf-7570-4231-8100-23544cff5baa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "95b57443-3696-49c6-bfc3-001aa3ab9497"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e175d428-c18f-4c71-ab37-2ea69055eb41",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to remind students of the steps students will take today.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to complete**Narrowing Your Focus** in their activity guide (page 4). Remind them to clarify their focus, audience, evidence, and solutions before drafting their campaign message. Display the guiding questions to keep them on track.\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> \n\n in their activity guide (page 4). Remind them to clarify their focus, audience, evidence, and solutions before drafting their campaign message. Display the guiding questions to keep them on track.\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check for clear, concise messaging and ask guiding questions like, “What is your key message?” and “Is your solution realistic and actionable?” Encourage students to refine their ideas for a strong, persuasive pitch.**Teaching Tip**\n\n**Teaching Tip**\n\nConsider having students choose new roles for today’s tasks. Let the Timekeeper know that they should give their group about seven minutes for this step.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display part 1 of the example pitch and ask for volunteers to read it aloud or have students read it silently.\n\n**Teaching Tip:**If you suspect you will be short on time, you might choose to provide printed copies of these example pitch slides to groups as a reference while drafting their own pitch.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display part 2 of the example pitch and ask for volunteers to read it aloud or have students read it silently.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Display part 3 of the example pitch and ask for volunteers to read it aloud or have students read it silently.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Instruct students to use their responses from Narrowing Your Focus to draft a 1-minute pitch summarizing their focus, audience, evidence, and solutions using bullet points, visuals, or full paragraphs.\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> \n\n Instruct students to use their responses from Narrowing Your Focus to draft a 1-minute pitch summarizing their focus, audience, evidence, and solutions using bullet points, visuals, or full paragraphs.\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are structuring their pitch clearly and including key elements. Ask guiding questions like, “Does your pitch clearly communicate your message?” and “Would your audience understand what action to take?” Provide quick feedback to help students refine their ideas.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Teaching Tip:**Consider using a timer (about 7 minutes) to keep students on track. Encourage students to focus on clarity and persuasion rather than perfection—this is a draft for feedback.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Instruct students to gather peer feedback using the “One Stay, Two Stray” protocol. Use the slide to explain the procedure to students.\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> \n\n Instruct students to gather peer feedback using the “One Stay, Two Stray” protocol. Use the slide to explain the procedure to students.\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Encourage students to give specific feedback by asking: ‘What was strong about this campaign? What could be improved?’ If a campaign lacks a clear call to action, prompt reviewers to ask: ‘What specific action does this campaign want people to take?",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "- Depending on group size, you may want to have two students stay—one to present and one to take notes—while the others rotate.\n- Depending on classroom structure, you may want to assign group numbers before the activity to ensure students rotate in sequence (e.g., Group 1 moves to Group 2, Group 2 moves to Group 3, etc.) for a smoother transition."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e175d428-c18f-4c71-ab37-2ea69055eb41",
        "lesson_activity.key": "95b57443-3696-49c6-bfc3-001aa3ab9497"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d01712fe-cdc6-4567-a6c1-fe5efee08034",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d01712fe-cdc6-4567-a6c1-fe5efee08034",
        "lesson_activity.key": "95b57443-3696-49c6-bfc3-001aa3ab9497"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46887bea-c679-4386-8847-e87911cdcd95",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the sample peer feedback responses to model effective peer feedback and clarify any confusion students might have.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the sample peer feedback responses to model effective peer feedback and clarify any confusion students might have.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the sample peer feedback responses to model effective peer feedback and clarify any confusion students might have.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:**  Direct students to review their Peer Review Feedback Checklist and discuss which feedback was most helpful. Have them decide what revisions will improve clarity, persuasiveness, and feasibility, then make adjustments to their campaign. Remind them they will have 20 minutes next class for final touches before presenting.\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> \n\n Direct students to review their Peer Review Feedback Checklist and discuss which feedback was most helpful. Have them decide what revisions will improve clarity, persuasiveness, and feasibility, then make adjustments to their campaign. Remind them they will have 20 minutes next class for final touches before presenting.\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Encourage students to prioritize impactful revisions and refine their messaging. If a group is struggling, ask guiding questions like, “What change would make your argument stronger?” or “How can you make your message clearer for your audience?”"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46887bea-c679-4386-8847-e87911cdcd95",
        "lesson_activity.key": "95b57443-3696-49c6-bfc3-001aa3ab9497"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "160657a0-02a4-45ee-abff-d88fdb310957",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
